# Semantic HTML

## Requirement

All HTML files SHALL use semantic HTML5 elements instead of generic `<div>` and `<span>` elements where appropriate.

## Semantic Elements

HTML files SHALL prefer semantic elements over generic containers:

- `<header>` instead of `<div class="header">`
- `<nav>` instead of `<div class="nav">`
- `<main>` instead of `<div class="main">`
- `<article>` instead of `<div class="article">`
- `<section>` instead of `<div class="section">`
- `<aside>` instead of `<div class="sidebar">`
- `<footer>` instead of `<div class="footer">`

## Document Structure

HTML files SHALL use semantic elements to structure the document:

```html
<body>
  <header>
    <nav>...</nav>
  </header>
  <main>
    <article>
      <section>...</section>
    </article>
    <aside>...</aside>
  </main>
  <footer>...</footer>
</body>
```

## Lists

HTML files SHALL use proper list elements instead of divs for lists:

- `<ul>` for unordered lists
- `<ol>` for ordered lists
- `<dl>` for definition lists

```html
<ul>
  <li>Item 1</li>
  <li>Item 2</li>
</ul>
```

SHALL NOT use:

```html
<div class="list">
  <div class="item">Item 1</div>
  <div class="item">Item 2</div>
</div>
```

## Forms

HTML files SHALL use proper form elements and structure:

- Use `<form>` element to wrap form controls
- Use `<fieldset>` to group related form controls
- Use `<legend>` to provide a caption for fieldset
- Use proper input types (`type="email"`, `type="tel"`, etc.)

```html
<form>
  <fieldset>
    <legend>Contact Information</legend>
    <label for="email">Email:</label>
    <input type="email" id="email" name="email">
  </fieldset>
</form>
```

## Headings

HTML files SHALL use proper heading elements (`<h1>` through `<h6>`) for document structure:

- Headings SHALL reflect the document outline
- Headings SHALL NOT be used for styling purposes
- Headings SHALL maintain proper hierarchy (see `html/accessibility.mdc`)

## Text Semantics

HTML files SHALL use semantic text elements:

- `<strong>` for important text (not `<b>`)
- `<em>` for emphasized text (not `<i>`)
- `<mark>` for highlighted text
- `<time>` for dates and times
- `<address>` for contact information
- `<code>` for code snippets
- `<pre>` for preformatted text

## When to Use Div and Span

Generic `<div>` and `<span>` elements MAY be used when:

- No semantic element exists for the purpose
- The element is purely presentational and has no semantic meaning
- The element is used as a container for styling purposes only

However, semantic alternatives SHALL be preferred whenever possible.

## Template Engines

When using template engines, semantic HTML structure SHALL be maintained in the template files. Template syntax within semantic HTML is acceptable.
